<TITLE> Malawi leader threatens to close parliament over budget </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LILONGWE, August 14 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Malawi's President Bingu wa Mutharika said on Tuesday he would close parliament if a budget crisis was not resolved within two days. The budget debate, which should have been concluded by June 30, was indefinitely suspended last month because of a dispute on the poaching of members of the opposition by the ruling party. "I am giving them two days -- today and tomorrow -- and if today and tomorrow they do not start discussing seriously the budget, I am closing down the parliament," Wa Mutharika said in a speech monitored on state radio. "Parliament, especially the opposition, has abrogated their responsibility and as such they have therefore become irrelevant for the development of this country," wa Mutharika said in the eastern town of Balaka where he was on an official engagement. The opposition-led parliament has refused to vote on the annual budget because it first wants a dispute over the poaching of its members by the ruling party to to be resolved. Leaders in parliament were meeting on Tuesday afternoon to discuss what to 
